                                <td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><tr><td><a href="viewtopic.php?p=100124#100124"><img src="templates/subSilver/images/icon_minipost.gif" width="12" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" border="0" /></a><span class="postdetails">Posted: Tue Mar 29, 2005 4:07 pm<span class="gen">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp; &nbsp;Post subject: </span></td>
                                <td align="right" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><a href="posting.php?mode=quote&amp;p=100124"><img src="templates/subSilver/images/lang_english/icon_quote.gif" alt="Reply with quote" title="Reply with quote" border="0" /></a>    </td></tr></table></td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Tolsonor wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">I understand your points Yakk...
<br />

<br />
1)  Did Tank durability increase first or mob DPS?  It's the old-- which came first?  the chicken or the egg quandry.   In either case, how can SOE justify scaling mob DPS or Tank durability out of proportion to every other class durability? ( in particular Enc)  This is exactly the scaling type fault I believe is the underliying problem.  Why not simply scale-up Mob DPS and/or Tank durability proportionately in the context of the other class advances?,  That way most other classes don't get left behind in this regard?
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I bet they probably -thought- that everyone else would scale too, but it really hasn't worked out that way due to all the stupid junk like AC caps etc.  I mean, I have maybe 2/3rds to 3/4th the HPs of a similarly geared tank, more if you count Rune, but it sure doesn't take it 2/3rds to 3/4ths of the time it takes to kill the tank to kill me. =P</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
	<tr>
		<td class="row1" width="150" align="left" valign="middle"><span class="nav"><a href="#top" class="nav">Back to top</a></span></td>
		<td class="row1" width="100%" height="28" valign="bottom" nowrap="nowrap"><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0" height="18" width="18"><tr><td valign="absbottom" nowrap="nowrap"><span class="gensmall"><a href="./profile.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=524"><img src="templates/subSilver/images/lang_english/icon_profile.gif" border="0" alt="View user's profile" title="View user's profile" /></a>&nbsp;</span></td></tr></table></td>
	</tr>
        <tr>
                <td class="spaceRow" colspan="2" height="1"><img src="templates/subSilver/images/spacer.gif" alt="" width="1" height="1" /></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
		<td width="150" align="left" valign="top" class="row2"><a name="100126"></a><span class="name"><span class="usercolor">Yakk</span></span></td>
                <td class="row2" width="100%" height="28" valign="top"><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
                        <tr>
                                <td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><tr><td><a href="viewtopic.php?p=100126#100126"><img src="templates/subSilver/images/icon_minipost.gif" width="12" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" border="0" /></a><span class="postdetails">Posted: Tue Mar 29, 2005 4:32 pm<span class="gen">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp; &nbsp;Post subject: </span></td>
                                <td align="right" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><a href="posting.php?mode=quote&amp;p=100126"><img src="templates/subSilver/images/lang_english/icon_quote.gif" alt="Reply with quote" title="Reply with quote" border="0" /></a>    </td></tr></table></td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">1) Did Tank durability increase first or mob DPS? It's the old-- which came first? the chicken or the egg quandry. In either case, how can SOE justify scaling mob DPS or Tank durability out of proportion to every other class durability? ( in particular Enc) This is exactly the scaling type fault I believe is the underliying problem. Why not simply scale-up Mob DPS and/or Tank durability proportionately in the context of the other class advances?, That way most other classes don't get left behind in this regard? </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
They wanted to remove the 'gear-flation' problem in which a well geared non-tank was a way better tank than a low-gear tank.
<br />

<br />
The difference between tanks and non-tanks was small enough that a relatively small gear level difference made tanks lose their jobs.
<br />

<br />
Second, the healing paradymn shifted with increased player mana regen.  Back in the day, burst healing was way higher than sustained healing: now, burst healing is at best twice as fast as sustained healing.  This means that mana regen is far less of an issue, and 'can you stay alive' becomes more central.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">2) I don't deny that their have been some great and innovative Group encounters written for the game...and I applaud those developers and coders. Also, I don't deny that there are players that enjoy them, but get serious...the majority of players don't spend their online time in those "15 interesting group encounters" you speak of. Do a /who while you are /LFG nowadays and see what zones peeps are in. They are in the XP grind zones -- the "hot" Zones -- or in raids. I have a hot button set up to check level ranges of peeps online when I log on. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Because there is no way to progress between them by doing them.
<br />

<br />
You can do Tipt until the cows come home, and that won't prepare you for the next interesting group encounter.
<br />

<br />
At best, those rare interesting group encounters are spice and something you do to break the mold.
<br />

<br />
Imagine if every raider had to spend 20 hours grinding mobs to earn the ability to do a 2 hour raid encounter.  Guess where all the raiders would be most of the time?  Grinding mobs.
<br />

<br />
Instead, raid encounters are designed so that you can spend more time doing them than you do not doing them.  They have progression built into them.
<br />

<br />
If single group encounters where just as rich, you'd have people progressing through them like they do raid encounters.
<br />

<br />
I personally spend most of my online grouping time in such encounters.  The only reason why I can do this is because I belong to a raiding guild that progresses at a particular rate and I play at a certain rate, I can farm easy-to-get gear from raids, and use it to progress through those encounters.
<br />

<br />
Look at raiders: most of them didn't do the Ring of Fire in Acrylia or the Dragon ring in Velious, because they where long, hard and had sub-par rewards.
<br />

<br />
Tipt is a zone with very hard mobs and a 3 hour crawl, without special tactics, that results in 1 random good drop for 1 person.
<br />

<br />
If they made a while raft of tipt-like zones, with a good RvR, that allowed you to gear up and progress through such content, you'd see people doing them.
<br />

<br />
And not with a cheesy pure-point system like DoN/LDoN please.  Have points <span style="font-weight: bold">and</span> drops required for items if you must.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Did anything inherent to our Class (ENC) change significantly in a truly unbalanced kind of way? -- NO. (meaning to OUR advantage)</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Enchanters gained the ability to use 'normal mezzes' on red-con content, something that wasn't true since L 55 in Kunark.  Enchanters gained the ability to charm barely-blue con content, something that hasn't been true since L 54.  The resit changes made our debuffs and mezzes and charms more reliable and less random.  Total Domination did the same.  Low level slows with very cheap mana costs continue to completely gimp harder and harder mobs.  We gained the ability to do PBAOE defence against even-con mobs.  Arcane Rune gave us tanking ability like we had never seen before.
<br />

<br />
All of these are potentially game breaking problems.  To each of them, a defensive nerf was applied.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Unmei wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">I bet they probably -thought- that everyone else would scale too, but it really hasn't worked out that way due to all the stupid junk like AC caps etc. I mean, I have maybe 2/3rds to 3/4th the HPs of a similarly geared tank, more if you count Rune, but it sure doesn't take it 2/3rds to 3/4ths of the time it takes to kill the tank to kill me. =P</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Starting in PoP, gear has followed the pattern:
<br />
Cloth 3 AC
<br />
Leather 5 AC
<br />
Chain 8 AC
<br />
Plate 10 AC
<br />

<br />
Look at the LDoN augments or the tradeskilled DoN gear.
<br />

<br />
Because of this, silk class AC hasn't moved since Luclin/Velious.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
